To make your Auto Scaling Group (ASG) "self-healing," you need to configure a Health Check. This ensures that if your Node.js process crashes or the server hangs, AWS will automatically terminate that instance and launch a fresh one to replace it.
Here is the step-by-step configuration for a robust health check:
## 1. Update your Node.js Code (The Health Endpoint)
Add a specific /health route to your app.js. This allows the Load Balancer to check if the app is actually responding, rather than just checking if the server is "on."

const http = require('http');
const server = http.createServer((req, res) => {
  // Health Check Endpoint
  if (req.url === '/health') {
    res.statusCode = 200;
    res.end('OK');
    return;
  }

  // Your main app logic
  res.statusCode = 200;
  res.setHeader('Content-Type', 'text/plain');
  res.end('Hello from ' + require('os').hostname() + '\n');
});

server.listen(3000, '0.0.0.0');

## 2. Configure the Target Group Health Check
In the AWS Console, go to EC2 > Target Groups and select the group you created for your Node.js app.

   1. Click the Health checks tab -> Edit.
   2. Health check path: Change / to /health.
   3. Advanced health check settings:
   * Healthy threshold: 2 (Number of consecutive successful checks before considering it "Healthy").
      * Unhealthy threshold: 3 (Number of failed checks before the Load Balancer stops sending traffic).
      * Timeout: 5 seconds.
      * Interval: 30 seconds.
   
## 3. Link the ASG to the Load Balancer Health Check
By default, an Auto Scaling Group only checks if the EC2 instance is "running." It doesn't know if your Node.js app has crashed. You must tell it to listen to the Load Balancer.

   1. Go to EC2 > Auto Scaling Groups.
   2. Select your group -> Details tab -> Health checks section -> Edit.
   3. Check the box: Enable ELB health checks (Elastic Load Balancing).
   4. Health check grace period: Set this to 300 seconds (5 minutes).
   * Why? This gives your User Data script enough time to install Node.js and start the app before AWS starts "testing" it. If this is too short, AWS might kill the instance before it even finishes booting up!
   
## 4. How to Test the "Self-Healing"
Want to see it in action?

   1. SSH into one of your running instances.
   2. Stop the Node.js process manually: pm2 stop all.
   3. Wait about 2-3 minutes.
   4. Watch the Console: You will see the Load Balancer mark the instance as Unhealthy. Shortly after, the Auto Scaling Group will terminate that instance and automatically start a brand-new one to maintain your "Desired Capacity."

## Summary of the Flow

   1. Node.js App: Exposes /health.
   2. Load Balancer (ALB): Pings /health every 30 seconds.
   3. Target Group: Reports "Unhealthy" if the app stops responding.
   4. ASG: Sees the "Unhealthy" status from the ALB and replaces the instance.

