Core Architecture Components
Application Load Balancer (ALB): Acts as the entry point, distributing incoming requests across your fleet of Node.js instances.
Launch Template: A blueprint containing the instance configuration (AMI with Node.js installed, instance type, security groups, and key pairs).
Auto Scaling Group (ASG): Manages the fleet based on the launch template, maintaining a specific number of instances (minimum, maximum, and desired capacity). 

Step-by-Step Setup Example
1. Prepare your Node.js Environment
Create an AMI: Set up a base EC2 instance, install Node.js, and clone your application code.
Health Check Endpoint: Ensure your Node.js app (using Express, Hapi, etc.) has a simple route like /status that returns a 200 OK.
Create Image: Once the instance is ready, use the Amazon EC2 Console to "Create Image" (AMI) from that instance. 

2. Create a Launch Template
Go to the Launch Templates section in the EC2 dashboard.
Select the AMI you just created.
Choose an Instance Type (e.g., t2.micro for testing).
Configure a Security Group that allows traffic on the port your Node.js app uses (e.g., port 3000 or 8080). 

3. Set Up the Auto Scaling Group (ASG)
Create a new ASG and link it to your Launch Template.
Configure Group Size: Set your minimum (e.g., 2), maximum (e.g., 10), and desired capacity (e.g., 2) to ensure high availability.
Attach Load Balancer: Select "Attach to an existing load balancer" and choose your Target Group (which routes traffic from the ALB to your instances). 

4. Define Scaling Policies
Choose how you want the fleet to grow or shrink: 
Target Tracking: Keep average CPU utilization at 50%. AWS will add/remove instances to maintain this.
Scheduled Scaling: Scale up every Monday morning or before a known sales event. 


